{"sections":[{"id":"input-output","title":"Input and Output","status":"dev","background":"","goals":0,"duration":5,"steps":["step-0"]},{"id":"graphing","title":"Graphing Functions","status":"dev","background":"","goals":0,"duration":5,"steps":["step-1"]},{"id":"slope-intercept","title":"Slope and Intercept","status":"dev","background":"","goals":16,"duration":20,"steps":["slope","questions-1","intercept","equation","equation-1","questions-2"]},{"id":"parallel-perpendicular","title":"Parallel and Perpendicular Lines","status":"dev","background":"","goals":0,"duration":5,"steps":["step-8"]},{"id":"linear","title":"Linear Functions","status":"dev","background":"","goals":0,"duration":5,"steps":["step-9"]},{"id":"systems","title":"Piecewise Functions and Systems of Equations","status":"dev","background":"","goals":0,"duration":5,"steps":["step-10"]}],"steps":[{"section":"input-output","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"step-0","goals":[],"html":"<x-step id=\"step-0\" goals=\"\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">TODO</span></p></x-step>"},{"section":"graphing","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"step-1","goals":[],"html":"<x-step id=\"step-1\" goals=\"\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">TODO</span></p></x-step>"},{"section":"slope-intercept","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"slope","goals":["make-point","slide-point","blank-0","next-0"],"html":"<x-step id=\"slope\" goals=\"make-point slide-point blank-0 next-0\"><div class=\"theorem\"> <p><span class=\"sentence\"><strong>Common Core Standard 8.EE.6</strong></span><br><span class=\"sentence\">Use similar triangles to explain why the slope <em>m</em> is the same between any two distinct points on a non-vertical line in the coordinate plane; derive the equation <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals mx\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi></span> for a line through the origin and the equation <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals mx plus b\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>b</mi></span> for a line intercepting the vertical axis at <em>b</em>.</span></p></div> <p><span class=\"sentence\">Here you can see a <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"coordinate-system\">coordinate system</x-gloss>,</span> with a straight line that goes through its <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"coordinate-system-origin\">origin</x-gloss>.</span> </span><span class=\"sentence\">To get started, pick a point anywhere on the line.</span></p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 360px\"> <x-coordinate-system class=\"c-system\" width=\"360\" height=\"440\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-6,6,1\" crosshairs=\"no\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system><x-gesture target=\"#slope x-coordinate-system\" offset=\"63,-107\"></x-gesture></div><div class=\"grow\"> <p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"make-point\"><span class=\"sentence\"> We can draw a right-angled triangle between this point and the origin of the coordinate system.</span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"make-point\" data-delay=\"1500\"><span class=\"sentence\"> Try sliding the point along the line: </span><span class=\"sentence\">notice how different points form differently sized triangles, but they are all <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank><button class=\"choice\">similar</button><button class=\"choice\">congruent</button><button class=\"choice\">equilateral</button></x-blank>.</span> </span><em class=\"lgrey reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\"><span class=\"sentence\"> The best way to see this is to look at the two angles along the x-axis. </span><span class=\"sentence\">They are always the same size, so by the <x-gloss xid=\"triangle-aa\">AA-condition</x-gloss> the triangles must all be similar.</span></em></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\" data-delay=\"1500\"><span class=\"sentence\"> Now we can use one of the results we know about similar triangles: </span><span class=\"sentence\">the ratio of two of the sides is always constant. </span><span class=\"sentence\">Move the point again, and watch what happens:</span></p><p class=\"text-center reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\" data-delay=\"3000\"><span class=\"sentence\"><span class=\"math\"><mfrac><mrow><span class=\"step-target pill var green\" data-to=\"dy\">${p.y}</span></mrow><mrow><span class=\"step-target pill var blue\" data-to=\"dx\">${p.x}</span></mrow></mfrac><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn class=\"var\">${p.y/p.x || '???'}</mn></span></span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"slide-point\"><span class=\"sentence\"> But the opposite is also true: </span><span class=\"sentence\">any point (<em>x</em>, <em>y</em>) that satisfies this equation must lie somewhere on the line. </span><span class=\"sentence\">Therefore we now have an “equation” for the line:</span></p><p class=\"text-center reveal\" data-when=\"slide-point\" data-delay=\"1000\"><span class=\"sentence\"><span class=\"math\"><mfrac><mrow><mi class=\"step-target pill green\" data-to=\"dy\">y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi class=\"step-target pill blue\" data-to=\"dx\">x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>1.5</mn></span></span></p><p class=\"r text-center reveal\" data-when=\"slide-point\" data-delay=\"2000\"><span class=\"sentence\"><span class=\"math\"><mo value=\"⇔\">⇔</mo><mi class=\"step-target pill green\" data-to=\"dy\">y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>1.5</mn><mi class=\"step-target pill blue\" data-to=\"dx\">x</mi></span><button class=\"next-step\">Continue</button></span></p></div></div> </x-step>"},{"id":"questions-1","section":"slope-intercept","goals":["blank-0","blank-1","blank-2"],"html":"<x-step id=\"questions-1\" goals=\"blank-0 blank-1 blank-2\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">It turns out that <em>every line</em> that goes through the origin of a coordinate system has an equation of the form <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals mx\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mi>mx</mi></span>,</span> where <em>m</em> is called the <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-gloss xid=\"line-slope\"><strong>slope</strong></x-gloss>.</span></span></p><p><span class=\"sentence\">If you’re given a line, you can find the corresponding value of <em>m</em> by picking any point that lies on the line and simply dividing its <em>y</em> and <em>x</em> value. </span><span class=\"sentence\">Here are a few examples:</span></p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank-input solution=\"0.5\"></x-blank-input></span></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank-input solution=\"3\"></x-blank-input></span></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <em>m</em> = <x-blank-input solution=\"-1\"></x-blank-input></span></p></div></div> </x-step>"},{"id":"intercept","section":"slope-intercept","goals":["blank-0","var-0"],"html":"<x-step id=\"intercept\" goals=\"blank-0 var-0\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">But what about lines that <em>don’t</em> go through the origin of the coordinate system? </span><span class=\"sentence\">In that case we need one more component: </span><span class=\"sentence\">we can take the line with the same slope that goes through the origin, and shift it along the <em>y</em>-axis by adding or subtracting a number:</span></p><svg style=\"width: 0; height: 0; position: absolute;\"><defs><marker id=\"blue-arrow\" refX=\"2\" refY=\"2\" markerWidth=\"4\" markerHeight=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M 0 0 L 4 2 L 0 4 z\" fill=\"#fd8c00\"></path></marker><marker id=\"blue-circle\" refX=\"2\" refY=\"2\" markerWidth=\"4\" markerHeight=\"4\" orient=\"auto\"><circle cx=\"2\" cy=\"2\" r=\"1.5\" fill=\"#fd8c00\"></circle></marker></defs></svg><x-coordinate-system width=\"400\" height=\"320\" x-axis=\"-8,8,1\" y-axis=\"-6,6,1\" crosshairs=\"no\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system><x-gesture target=\"#intercept x-var\" slide=\"100,0\"></x-gesture><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals 2 over 3 x\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi></span> <span class=\"var\">${sign(a)}</span> <x-var bind=\"a|0|-4,4,1\">${abs(a)}</x-var></span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"var-0\"><span class=\"sentence\"> As you can see above, the number added to the value of <em>y</em> is the same as the distance between the origin of the coordinate system, and the point where the line crosses the <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank><button class=\"choice\"><em>y</em>-axis</button><button class=\"choice\"><em>x</em>-axis</button></x-blank>.</span></span></p></x-step>"},{"id":"equation","section":"slope-intercept","goals":["next-0"],"html":"<x-step id=\"equation\" goals=\"next-0\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">We now have an equation for <em>any</em> (non-vertical) line in the coordinate plane:</span></p><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"><span class=\"math\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mtext class=\"b i orange\">m</mtext><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mtext class=\"b i cyan\">b</mtext><mtext>,</mtext></span></span></p><p class=\"r\"><span class=\"sentence\"> where <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> and <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> are two numbers we have to fill in. </span><span class=\"sentence\">As you saw before, <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> is the <strong class=\"orange\">slope</strong> of the line, and <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> is the <strong class=\"cyan\"><em>y</em>-axis intercept</strong>. </span><span class=\"sentence\"><button class=\"next-step\"> Continue</button></span></p></x-step>"},{"id":"equation-1","section":"slope-intercept","goals":["blank-0","blank-1","eqn-0"],"html":"<x-step id=\"equation-1\" goals=\"blank-0 blank-1 eqn-0\"><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 360px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"360\" height=\"360\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,6,1\" no-crosshairs=\"no-crosshairs\" padding=\"5\"></x-coordinate-system></div><div class=\"grow\"> <p><span class=\"sentence\">If you’re given any line, like the one on the left, you can find the value of <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> by looking at the point where the line crosses the <em>y</em>-axis. </span><span class=\"sentence\">In this example, <em class=\"b cyan\">b</em> = <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank-input solution=\"2\"></x-blank-input>.</span></span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0\"><span class=\"sentence\"> Similarly, you can find the slope <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> by drawing any triangle below the line, and dividing its height and base. </span><span class=\"sentence\">In this example, the slope is <em class=\"b orange\">m</em> = <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank-input solution=\"0.75\"></x-blank-input>.</span></span></p><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-1\"><span class=\"sentence\"> In other words, the equation of this line is</span></p><p class=\"text-center reveal\" data-when=\"blank-1\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"3/4 x+2\"></x-equation></span></p></div></div> </x-step>"},{"id":"questions-2","section":"slope-intercept","goals":["eqn-0","eqn-1","eqn-2"],"html":"<x-step id=\"questions-2\" goals=\"eqn-0 eqn-1 eqn-2\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">Here are a few more exercises. </span><span class=\"sentence\">Can you find the slope and <em>y</em>-intercept in each case, and write down the equation of the line?</span></p><div class=\"row padded padded-thin\"><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"3/2 x-2\"></x-equation></span></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"2x+1\"></x-equation></span></p></div><div style=\"width: 230px\"> <x-coordinate-system width=\"230\" height=\"180\" x-axis=\"-5,5,1\" y-axis=\"-4,4,1\" labels=\"no\" padding=\"5\" crosshair-grid=\"1\"></x-coordinate-system><p class=\"text-center\"><span class=\"sentence\"> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"y equals\"><mi>y</mi><mo value=\"=\">=</mo></span> <x-equation solution=\"-1/2 x+3\"></x-equation></span></p></div></div> </x-step>"},{"section":"parallel-perpendicular","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"step-8","goals":[],"html":"<x-step id=\"step-8\" goals=\"\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">TODO</span></p></x-step>"},{"section":"linear","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"step-9","goals":[],"html":"<x-step id=\"step-9\" goals=\"\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">TODO</span></p></x-step>"},{"section":"systems","sectionStatus":"dev","id":"step-10","goals":[],"html":"<x-step id=\"step-10\" goals=\"\"><p><span class=\"sentence\">TODO</span></p></x-step>"}],"goals":16,"title":"Linear Functions"}